den Bauten eines Alfred Messel und eines Ludwig Mies van der Rohe.  aThe Middle Ages are still present today in the form of many objects, monuments, manuscripts, and buildings. The term ‘Medium Aevum,’ coined in the late Middle Ages and the Renaissance, suggested a broad construction of the medieval period. Since the Enlightenment, historical views of the Middle Ages have generated new forms of cultural memory, as reflected in contemporary art works that show the continued presence of the Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aEuropexHistory. 0aMiddle AgesxHistoriography. 0aMiddle Ages. 4aHumanismus. 4aKulturgut. 4aMittelalter. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aMiddle Ages.  acultural artifact.  ahumanism.1 aBorgolte, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA History 2000 - 2014z9783110635836oZDB-23-GHI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruyterteBook-Paket OWV/AV  Geschichte 2013z9783110342673oZDB-23-OGS0 cprintz978305006369040uhttps://doi.org/10.1524/978305009543140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783050095431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783050095431/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GHIc2000d2014  aZDB-23-OGSb2013